# Deliveries

[Deliveries](/deliveries) are a central element of CSA Admin and allow you to manage all the delivery dates of your <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %> throughout the year. Deliveries are one of the first elements to create. It's important that **all delivery dates** are defined **before the start of your fiscal year** because the creation of memberships and their <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %> depends on it.

The next delivery as well as its number of <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %>/<%= BasketComplement.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %> per depot are always available from [the dashboard](/dashboard). Each delivery page also contains this information as well as the list of absent members.

> You can easily create batch deliveries using the "Multiple dates" tab in [the delivery creation form](/deliveries/new).

## Delivery cycles {#delivery-cycles}

Some organizations offer different delivery choices, for example:

- deliveries on Mondays or Thursdays.
- deliveries every week or every other week.
- deliveries only in winter or summer.

[Delivery cycles](/delivery_cycles) allow you to dynamically group existing deliveries from the same fiscal year according to your needs and thus offer you great flexibility in managing your deliveries. Each membership is associated with a delivery cycle, which determines its delivery dates and the number of <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %>.

### Settings {#settings}

Settings define the initial selection of deliveries for this cycle. These filters are applied first:

- **Days**: Select which days of the week are included (e.g., Mondays only).
- **From week / Until week**: Limit deliveries to a specific range of week numbers. Useful for seasonal cycles (e.g., week 18 to week 42 for a summer season). When both boundaries are set, an **"Exclude week range"** option becomes available to invert the logic—excluding deliveries inside the range instead of outside (e.g., to skip a holiday period).

### Periods {#periods}

Periods then apply additional filtering to the deliveries selected by the settings above. They divide the fiscal year into segments, each with its own rules. This two-step approach (settings → periods) gives you fine-grained control over which deliveries are included.

Each delivery cycle must have at least one period. Periods cannot overlap within the same cycle.

Each period has the following options:

- **From month / To month**: Define the fiscal year month range this period applies to (e.g., January to June for a first semester).
- **Delivery selection**: Within the period's month range, determines which deliveries are kept (e.g., all, every other, first of each month, etc.).

This allows for flexible configurations, such as weekly deliveries during summer months and bi-weekly deliveries during winter, all within the same delivery cycle.

### Depot availability

The availability of each delivery cycle can be configured by depot; for example, one depot may only offer Monday deliveries, another only Thursdays, while a last one will let members choose during registration.

The choice of a delivery cycle on the registration form depends on the configuration of their availability by depot. In any case, the choice of delivery cycle is offered to members only if at least two delivery cycles are available for a visible depot.

> When creating a membership by an admin, it's always possible to choose any delivery cycle. <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2) %> will be automatically created based on the deliveries of this cycle between the start and end dates ✨.

### Even distribution (every other week) {#even-odd-distribution}

If you offer every-other-week deliveries, you probably want to distribute members evenly between even and odd weeks. A single "every other" cycle would assign the same weeks to all members.

The solution is to create **two separate cycles**, one with the delivery selection "Even" and the other "Odd", then make **only one visible** to members on the registration form:

1. Create two cycles, each with a period covering the full year: one with the delivery selection "Even", the other "Odd".
2. Give them the **same name**, e.g. "Every other week", but different **internal names**, e.g. "Every other week (even)" and "Every other week (odd)".
3. Make **only one** of the two cycles visible on the registration form (via depot availability).
4. When creating memberships, manually distribute members between the two cycles to balance deliveries.

This way, members see only one "Every other week" option at registration, but you keep control of the distribution internally.

### Billing

Each delivery cycle can have its own billing options:

- **Price (per delivery)**: An additional fee for the management and/or delivery with this cycle.
- **Name (invoice)**: A custom name displayed on invoices instead of the default delivery cycle name.
- **Absences included annually**: Automatically exclude a certain number of deliveries, enabling members to plan a limited number of non-billed absences. See [Included Absences](/handbook/absence#absence-included) for more details.

## Alternate depot {#alternate-depot}

Some members need to pick up their <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %> at different depots depending on the week — for example, because the CSA vehicle only serves a given depot every other week. CSA Admin supports this through an **alternate depot** configuration at the membership level.

This configuration is only available to administrators (not to members) and can be found in the membership edit form, under the collapsible "Alternate depot" section within the delivery settings. Three fields must be set together:

- **Alternate depot**: The second pickup location.
- **Alternate depot price**: The depot price for deliveries at the alternate depot (defaults to the depot's price).
- **Alternate delivery cycle**: Determines which deliveries go to the alternate depot. All other deliveries go to the main depot.

> **Example**: A membership uses the "Every week" cycle. The CSA vehicle only passes by the bakery depot every other week (even weeks), so the member picks up at the farm on the other weeks. The main depot is set to "Bakery" with the alternate depot set to "Farm" and the alternate delivery cycle set to "Odd weeks". Result: even-week <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %> go to the bakery, odd-week <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %> go to the farm.

A few important points:

- The alternate delivery cycle **must differ from the main cycle** of the membership and share at least one delivery with it.
- **Pricing** works automatically — each <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> is billed at the price of its respective depot.
- When a membership is **renewed**, the alternate depot configuration is automatically carried over.
- If a member changes their **main depot** from the member area, the alternate depot configuration is preserved.

## Individual <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> modifications {#basket-overrides}

Each <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> of a membership can be edited individually to deviate from the membership configuration: a different depot, a different <%= BasketSize.model_name.human.downcase %>, an adjusted quantity, custom <%= BasketComplement.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %>, or even a swap to another delivery date (in the context of another delivery cycle). These per-<%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> modifications are **preserved** when the membership configuration changes later (for example, when the <%= BasketSize.model_name.human.downcase %> or depot is updated from the given date).

On the membership page, any <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> that diverges from the membership configuration shows a small **history icon** next to its state. Hovering over the icon reveals who made the change (admin name, or "by the member") and when, along with the list of modified fields. From there, an **"Undo"** button restores the <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> to the membership defaults.

A few important points:

- Modifications are captured automatically whenever an admin edits a <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> or a member changes their depot or <%= BasketComplement.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %> from the member area (if allowed in [the membership settings](/settings#membership)).
- When the membership configuration changes, modifications are reapplied on the recreated <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %>. Modifications that reference deliveries no longer covered by the membership (for example, after switching to a different delivery cycle) are cleaned up automatically.
- If the membership configuration is changed to match a previously modified <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %>, the modification becomes a no-op and the history icon disappears.

## <%= BasketComplement.model_name.human(count: 2) %> {#basket-complements}

[<%= BasketComplement.model_name.human(count: 2) %>](/basket_complements) often follow their own delivery cycle in a way that is difficult to program dynamically. It is therefore necessary, and this for each <%= BasketComplement.model_name.human.downcase %>, to define all the delivery dates where this complement is available or not. This operation must be carried out each year after the creation of new deliveries.

## Delivery sheets (PDFs) {#delivery-sheets}

For each delivery, CSA Admin generates PDF sheets that you can print and use at your depots. These sheets are available from each [delivery page](/deliveries) or from [the dashboard](/dashboard).

### Sheet modes {#sheet-modes}

Each depot can use one of two sheet modes (configurable in the depot settings):

- **Signature sheet** (default): A checklist where members sign next to their name upon pickup. Members are listed alphabetically, with a "Signature" column on the right.
- **Home delivery sheet**: Designed for delivery drivers. Includes each member's full address and their delivery note (if any) in the last column. Members can be manually reordered via drag & drop in the depot settings.

### Member info on sheets {#member-info}

A [setting](/settings#delivery) controls what additional information is displayed below each member's name on the sheets:

- **None** (default): Only the member's name.
- **Phone numbers**: The member's phone number(s) appear below their name.
- **Food note**: The member's food note (allergies, preferences) appears below their name.

This setting applies globally to all depots using the signature sheet mode. Home delivery sheets always show the address and delivery note regardless of this setting.

### Footer {#delivery-pdf-footer}

A custom footer text can be added to all delivery sheets via the [delivery PDF footer setting](/settings#delivery). This is useful for a reminder, a thank-you message, or practical information.

### Announcements {#announcements}

Short messages can be attached to specific depot/delivery combinations and will appear on the corresponding delivery sheets. See the dedicated [announcements handbook page](/handbook/announcements) for details.

## Delivery notifications {#delivery-notifications}

CSA Admin can automatically send email notifications related to deliveries:

### Depot delivery list {#depot-delivery-list-notifications}

Each depot can be configured with email addresses (in the depot's "Notifications" section). The day before each delivery, these addresses receive an email containing the list of members and their <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %>, along with PDF and XLSX attachments for the delivery sheets.

### <%= BasketComplement.model_name.human %> weekly summary {#complement-notifications}

Each <%= BasketComplement.model_name.human.downcase %> can be configured with email addresses (in the <%= BasketComplement.model_name.human.downcase %>'s "Notifications" section). Every Sunday morning, these addresses receive an email summarizing the total count of that complement needed for each delivery of the upcoming week.

> This is useful for external suppliers (e.g., a baker, a cheese maker) who need to know how much to prepare for the week ahead.
